<DOC><DOCNO> AP900528-0061 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-05-28-90 1726EDT</FILEID><FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     05-28 0390</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0404</SECOND><HEAD>Thunderstorms Abound In Southeast, Snow In Western Mountains</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Wet, stormy weather advanced across the southeastern quarter ofthe nation Monday, spinning off at least one tornado, and a strongstorm in the West blew snow across the mountains.   At midday, showers and thunderstorms reached over central andsouthern Ohio across southwestern Pennsylvania, western Maryland,Virginia, West Virginia, much of Kentucky, much of Tennessee, NorthCarolina, South Carolina, parts of Georgia, northwestern andsouthern Florida, southern Mississippi, southern and centralLouisiana, and eastern Texas.   A tornado touched down in eastern Kentucky, knocking out powerto a Rowan County water pumping station and overturning a hangarand destroying an office at a small airport, officials said. Noinjuries were reported.   State Trooper Lon Fields said the tornado overturned severalplanes at the Morehead-Rowan County Airport, blew debris ontoseveral others and apparently carried off two more.   A tornado touched down near Cave Run Lake, Ky., the NationalWeather Service said.   Severe weather watches were posted from northern Florida tosouthern Virginia and West Virginia.   By 7 a.m. the rainfall for May at Louisville, Ky., had reached10.72 inches, almost a quarter of an inch above the previous recordfor the whole month of May. And rain continued falling.   Rain and showers extended from southern California andWashington state to the Rockies as a strong spring storm movedacross southern California with gusty wind.   The storm dropped an inch of rain on Los Angeles, the weatherservice said. The previous record for the date was just 0.12 of aninch, in 1971.   Wind gusted to 40 mph during the morning at Show Low, Ariz.   Snow fell over the mountains of southern Utah, with rain atlower elevations, and headed into western Colorado.   Heavier rainfall during the six hours up to 2 p.m. EDT included1.81 inches at Goldsboro, N.C.; 1.51 inches at Myrtle Beach, S.C.;1.17 inches at Leesville, La.; and 1.05 inches at McComb, Miss.   Parts of California got record rainfall Sunday. Sacramento got1.56 inches, a record for the date, and downtown San Francisco got1.47 inches, a record for any date in May.   The nation's temperatures at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 43 atTruckee, Calif., to 95 at Beeville, Texas.   Monday's low for the Lower 48 was 35 at Hibbing, Minn.</TEXT></DOC>